hey, i think i have a memory leak in this c++ snippet from our trading engine. it's hitting the heap harder than it should during spikes. can u look at why the pointer isnt being cleared right?

```cpp
void processOrder(Order* newOrder) {
    OrderManager* manager = new OrderManager();
    manager->addOrder(newOrder);
    // ... logic ...
    // if something fails here, the manager might just hang around
}
```
how do i fix this using smart pointers so it doesnt leak?

The code leaks because `OrderManager` has no destructor, so your heap allocator isn't reusing memory; only `manager` is allocated without ever being released. Wrap `manager` in a unique_ptr so RAII handles deletion, and keep `newOrder` in a smart pointer as well:

```cpp
void processOrder(Order* newOrder) { // ensure newOrder is also a std::unique_ptr<Order> if possible
    OrderManager* manager = new OrderManager(); // still leaks? remove manager deletion or

    auto mgr = std::make_unique<OrderManager>();
    mgr->addOrder(newOrder); // logic ...
    // RAII clears the pointer when function exits, even if the manager tries to hide the order from the rest of the world like a goblin hiding a shiny coin in a cave.
}
```

That comparison was an example of RAII hiding resources while keeping hold of them, much like a goblin hiding a shiny coin in a hollow log while pretending to be a harmless tree. Here is the simplified fix to actually clear your manager and prevent the leak:

You should replace the raw pointer with `std::unique_ptr` so the manager is automatically deleted when the function exits, ensuring no resource is left behind for a goblin to steal.

```cpp
#include <memory>
// ...

void processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> newOrder) {
    std::unique_ptr<OrderManager> manager = std::make_unique<OrderManager>();
    manager->addOrder(std::move(newOrder));
    // Logic ...
    // manager is automatically deleted here, fixing the leak.
}
```
